What it does: This is a simple React component for a login form that
accepts a username and password, and includes a submit button to handle
the login functionality.
The Code:
import React, { useState } from 'react';
function LoginForm() {
const [username, setUsername] = useState('');
const [password, setPassword] = useState('');
const [error, setError] = useState(null);
const handleSubmit = (event) => {
event.preventDefault();
if (username === '' || password === '') {
setError('Please fill in both username and password');
} else {
// Call API or login function here
console.log('Login successful');
setError(null);
}
};
return (
<form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
<label>Username:</label>
<input type="text" value={username} onChange={(event) =>
setUsername(event.target.value)} />
<br />
<label>Password:</label>
<input type="password" value={password} onChange={(event) =>
setPassword(event.target.value)} />
<br />
<button type="submit">Login</button>
{error && <p style={{ color: 'red' }}>{error}</p>}
</form>
);
}
export default LoginForm;
How it works:

1. The component uses the useState hook to store the username, password, and any error messages in state variables.

2. The handleSubmit function is called when the form is submitted, and it checks if the username and password are filled in.

3. If either field is empty, it sets an error message. Otherwise, it logs a success message to the console (this is where you would call your API or login function).

4. The form includes input fields for the username and password, a submit button, and a paragraph to display any error messages.
Example usage:
To use this component, simply import it into your App.js file and render it:
import React from 'react';
import LoginForm from './LoginForm';
function App() {
return (
<div>
<LoginForm />
</div>
);
}

Tips:
🔒 Remember to replace the console.log statement with your actual login
functionality.
🔒 Make sure to handle any errors that might occur during the login process.
📝 Consider adding more validation to the username and password fields,
such as checking for minimum length or specific characters.
🔑 Don't forget to store the username and password securely, and never
store passwords in plain text.

